Fiction","startTime":null,"eventDescription":"High Fiction isn’t afraid of being labeled unconventional. The power duo has accompanied modern dance, played for weddings, accompanied two different gospel choirs, and even competed against themselves as six different bands in a Battle of the Bands competition. Their latest endeavor places them as hosts for a Variety Night at a secret location in Old Town Arvada.

“You basically have to know someone to get in. Or at least know who to ask,” keyboardist/singer Gary Grundei tells us over a rye whiskey drink called Sweater Weather. “We’re breaking a few rules by telling you all of this now.”

The duo is working on a full length album to be released early 2015. “We tend to leave the audience wanting more,” drummer/singer Amy Shelley tells us. “We aim to provide an intimate and magical evening.” The drinks at their secret venue where we met these two certainly don’t hinder that goal.

High Fiction has some impressive talent on the record so far: Matt Berninger, of The National, contributes vocals to a track entitled “The Young Men” and respected bandleaders Ron Miles and Janet Feder also add to the mix. And speaking of mix, the multitalented David Wilton, who writes his own music under the moniker A Boy and His Kite, is co-producing the album with Amy and Gary and will mix it as well.

I promise you this reporter will be there for Variety Night. With High Fiction, you just never know who will stop by.

For tickets to High Fiction presents Variety Night, go to high fiction.com/tickets

“Holy shit! That is phenomenal stuff. Seriously. Wow!” —Jeff F.
